DM instance that illustrated USP commands.

Note that the HTML shows commands as objects. They can be distinguished because command names do not end in periods.

Device.Operations. object -

Data model operations. This object is automatically maintained by the USP Agent.

  • The Commands object contains a table for each supported command, e.g. Commands.Reboot. These tables contain an entry for each active command.
  • The Request table contains an entry for each active request. Each Request references the corresponding command instance.
- 1.0
RequestNumberOfEntries unsignedInt - The number of entries in the Request table. - 1.0
Device.Operations.Commands. object - Active commands. - 1.0
RebootNumberOfEntries unsignedInt - The number of entries in the Reboot table. - 1.0
DownloadNumberOfEntries unsignedInt - The number of entries in the Download table. - 1.0

Target string - The value MUST be the path name of the object on which this command was invoked. If the referenced object is deleted, this instance MUST also be deleted (so the parameter value will never be an empty string). - 1.0

Device.Operations.Request.{i}. object -

Device operations. Request instances are created using USP Operate messages. Only Operate messages with async=true will create a Request instance in the data model.

An Operate message is associated with a command; commands are declared using the DM command element (a legacy CWMPv1 command parameter is a parameterless USP command).

XXX 2: CommandKey would be a unique key, but can't be because it might be empty. We could add a DM uniqueKey attribute to cover this case, or could require the device to assign a unique value when the Controller doesn't supply one. The latter is better?

At most one entry in this table can exist with a given value for Command.

 - 1.0
Command string -

The value MUST be the path name of a row in the Commands.Reboot or Commands.Download tables. If the referenced object is deleted, this instance MUST also be deleted (so the parameter value will never be an empty string).

XXX 3: It's not possible to list all the possible targets in this way. They should be listed by base type (Command) rather than by name.

 - 1.0
CommandKey string - The command key from the USP Operate message. - 1.0
State string -

Enumeration of:

  • Requested
  • Active
  • Canceling
  • Canceled
  • Success
  • Error
- 1.0
Message string - Generic error message. - 1.0
Detail string - Detailed error message. - 1.0
Cancel command -

Request cancelation of this Request's command.

This command completes immediately. If successul, State will immediately change to Canceling and will change to Canceled when the cancelation is complete.

 - 1.0
Delete command -

Request deletion of this Request instance.

This command completes immediately.

 - 1.0

Profile Definitions

Notation

The following abbreviations are used to specify profile requirements:

Abbreviation Description
R Read support is REQUIRED.
W Both Read and Write support is REQUIRED. This MUST NOT be specified for a parameter that is defined as read-only.
P The object is REQUIRED to be present.
C Creation and deletion of instances of the object via AddObject and DeleteObject is REQUIRED.
A Creation of instances of the object via AddObject is REQUIRED, but deletion is not REQUIRED.
D Deletion of instances of the object via DeleteObject is REQUIRED, but creation is not REQUIRED.
